skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:2:name: rhei-state-machine-writer
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Design and generate custom Rhei state machine YAML files from project specifications and team structures. Use when users need a workflow that doesn't fit the default rhei state machine — domain-specific phases, multi-team handoffs, approval gates, counted review loops, model-specific states, or automated callback integrations.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:8:Design a custom Rhei state machine only when the built-in `rhei` workflow is too generic. Produce a YAML file that matches the project's real phases, actors, gates, retries, and automation hooks, ready to be referenced by a plan's `**States:**` declaration.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:10:The state machine writer runs before the plan writer. It defines the workflow; the plan writer later uses that workflow.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:62:Emit one YAML file that conforms to the current Rhei state-machine format. The file has five sections: `name`/`version`, optional `models`, `states`, `transitions`, `profiles`, `node_policy`, and optional `callbacks` / `error_handling`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:64:When this skill is used from `rhei-template-writer`, emit template-ready YAML for `<template>/states.yaml`: include the full machine, preserve any needed `{{...}}` instantiation variables, and add the template-required ASCII diagram comment block before `name:`. Do not return only a transition sketch or prose description.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:75:- `node_policy`
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:92:> `initial: true` is **not** a state-level field. Initial states are declared on each profile under the top-level `profiles` block; `node_policy` routes each node to a profile.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:150:node_policy:
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:181:      <optional state-specific framing — supports template variables>
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:218:node_policy:
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:272:4. `node_policy.root` and `node_policy.default` are both required and must name defined profiles.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:281:5. Use template variables (`{task_id}`, `{task_title}`, `{visit_count}`, `{visits}`, `{model}`) instead of prose placeholders like `<id>`. When a state declares artifact contracts, reference them via `{input.<name>.path}` and `{output.<name>.path}` instead of repeating raw paths. Unknown variables are left verbatim, so free-form braces in prose are safe.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:299:7. Draft profiles and `node_policy`. Start with one default profile. Add `by_type` / `overrides` only when different kinds need different flows.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:301:9. Write the YAML file to `docs/states.yaml` or `docs/states/<name>.yaml` (or the `.agents/rhei/` paths — see *File Placement*).
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:304:If authoring for a Rhei Template, write the YAML to `<template>/states.yaml` instead and ensure the template's plan skeleton declares the same machine name with `**States:** <name>`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:319:- `inputs:` / `outputs:` paths are execution-root-relative and use template variables rather than hard-coded task ids.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:329:- `node_policy` is present with both `root` and `default`, both referencing defined profiles.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:333:If the `rhei` CLI is available, validate with:
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:336:rhei states --state-machine <path>
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:341:For template-authored machines that still contain `{{...}}` instantiation placeholders, do not validate the raw `<template>/states.yaml` directly. Instantiate the template first, then validate the rendered workspace's state machine.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:347:- `docs/states.yaml` — single machine for the project, auto-discovered by a sibling or workspace-root plan.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:349:- `.agents/rhei/states.yaml` / `.agents/rhei/states/<name>.yaml` — for projects that keep agent configuration under `.agents/`.
skills/rhei-state-machine-writer/SKILL.md:351:Plans normally pick up a sibling or workspace-root `states.yaml` automatically when they declare `**States:** <name>`. The YAML file's `name` must match the declaration. Use `--state-machine <path>` when overriding the conventional auto-discovered file.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:2:name: rhei-template-writer
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Design and generate Rhei Templates — parameterized, reusable bundles of a plan skeleton, optional state machine, optional settings, and a typed input manifest that can be instantiated with `rhei instantiate` to produce ready-to-execute workspaces. Use when users want to capture a recurring workflow (review loops, release checklists, onboarding, audits) once and instantiate it later with concrete inputs.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:8:Produce a Rhei Template directory — a manifest plus a plan skeleton (and, when needed, a state machine and settings) — that `rhei instantiate` can render into a concrete, executable workspace.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:10:The template writer runs before `rhei instantiate`. It packages a proven workflow; `rhei instantiate` materializes it with user-supplied inputs. It does not replace the plan writer or state machine writer — it composes their outputs into something reusable.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:14:Use this skill when a workflow is going to be instantiated more than once with the same shape but different inputs:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:20:- Any "scaffold a workspace" request where plans and state machines would otherwise be copy-pasted.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:25:- The user only needs a state machine — use `rhei-state-machine-writer` directly.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:30:Gather all three before designing the template. If anything is missing, ask and stop.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:47:- Does the workflow fit the built-in `rhei` state machine? If yes, bundle no `states.yaml`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:48:- Does it need a custom machine? If yes, author it via `rhei-state-machine-writer` and bundle it.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:49:- Does it need MCP servers, skills, or agents declared in `settings.json`? If yes, bundle one.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:53:A template is a directory. Required layout:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:57:├── template.yaml          # Manifest (required)
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:59:├── states.yaml            # State machine (optional — omit to use the built-in `rhei` default)
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:69:Every template must also ship a pre-rendered example workspace checked in elsewhere (see *Required Accompaniments*).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:71:When a custom state machine is needed, `states.yaml` is a required generated artifact, not background design notes. Produce the complete YAML file in the template directory, include it in any file-by-file response, and keep the rendered plan's `**States:** <name>` declaration aligned with `states.yaml:name`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:75:- The directory name is the template identifier. It must match `manifest.name` exactly.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:77:- `template.yaml` is parsed before rendering and is never templated itself. It is also excluded from the instantiated output.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:78:- Hidden files / directories (names beginning with `.`) and `template.yaml` are excluded from the output.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:79:- A root-level `settings.json` is moved to `.rhei/settings.json` in the output — do not write the `.rhei/` path in the template source.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:80:- Binary files (any file with null bytes in the first 8 KiB) are copied verbatim. Text files are rendered through the instantiation template environment and must decode as UTF-8.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:84:Every template must ship with three pieces of context alongside the skeleton itself. Omit any of them and the template is considered incomplete.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:86:### 1. `README.md` at the template root
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:88:One file at `<template>/README.md` describing:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:90:- What the template does (one-paragraph summary).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:92:- A short per-task-kind summary of how each task walks the state machine (a table is usually enough).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:94:- The canonical `rhei instantiate` invocation with representative `--set` arguments.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:97:Do not inline the state machine diagram here — it belongs in `states.yaml` comments (see below). Link to `states.yaml` from the README.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:99:The README is rendered through the instantiation environment like any other text file. Keep `{{...}}` out of it unless you want per-instantiation copies to diverge; generally the README documents the template itself, not the rendered output.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:101:### 2. State machine diagram as a comment block in `states.yaml`
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:103:When the template bundles a `states.yaml`, add an ASCII diagram as a YAML comment block at the very top of the file — before `name:`. The diagram must cover:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:112:This lives in the YAML file, not just the README, so anyone reading the state machine sees the picture without a context switch. If the template has no `states.yaml` (i.e., it uses the built-in `rhei` machine), skip this — the built-in is documented elsewhere.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:114:### 3. A pre-rendered example that passes `rhei validate`
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:116:For every template, check in one pre-rendered example so reviewers and users can see a working instantiation without running `rhei instantiate` themselves. The example is the template's smoke test.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:118:- Place it under `examples/<template-name>-example/` at the repo root (project conventions may vary; match what neighbouring templates do).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:119:- Generate it with `rhei instantiate <template> --set ... --output examples/<template-name>-example`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:120:- Overwrite the rendered `README.md` with an example-specific one that records the `--set` values used, the validate command, and the regenerate command. This keeps the template's own README as documentation and the example's README as an instantiation log.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:121:- The example must pass `rhei validate examples/<template-name>-example` as shipped.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:122:- Re-generate the example any time the template changes state shape, inputs, or the default rendering of the seed files.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:124:Pick inputs that exercise every non-trivial code path in the template — e.g., if there's a `focus_areas` input and an empty-list branch, set it to a non-empty list in the example so the rendered output demonstrates the branch. If one example can't reasonably cover every branch, pick the most interesting combination and note the trade-off in the example's README.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:126:## Manifest Contract (`template.yaml`)
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:130:version: <yaml-scalar>         # Informational; displayed by `rhei templates`
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:139:    validate: <regex>          # Rust regex applied to the rendered scalar value
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:155:- `validate` is only valid on scalar types (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, `path`).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:158:- Optional inputs with no `default` resolve to type-shaped empty values at instantiation time (`""` for `string`/`path`, `null` for `number`/`boolean`, `[]` for `array`, `{}` for `object`). Author the template to tolerate the empty value, or declare a `default`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:163:The instantiator uses a restricted MiniJinja environment. **Instantiation templates are distinct from Rhei runtime variables.** Both can coexist in the same file:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:167:| `{{ name }}` | `rhei instantiate` | `{{target}}` | At instantiation time |
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:168:| `{% ... %}` | `rhei instantiate` | `{% for t in targets %}...{% endfor %}` | At instantiation time |
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:194:3. **Use `validate` for format-shaped values.** Semver strings, slug identifiers, date fragments. Don't use it for open-ended free text.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:200:1. **Treat the skeleton like a plan authored by `rhei-plan-writer`.** It must pass `rhei validate` after rendering. Follow the plan writer's contract: exactly one H1 `# Rhei: <title>`, optional `**States:**`, `## Tasks` last (for single-file), tasks with `**State:**` first, `**Prior:**` second. A generated child task must never list its parent or any ancestor as `**Prior:**`; generate follow-up work as top-level sibling tasks when it must wait for the parent to complete.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:202:3. **Use `{{...}}` only where the plan actually depends on input.** A template that uses `{{target}}` in every task title is noisier than one that only interpolates where the value matters.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:208:1. **Omit `states.yaml` when the built-in `rhei` machine fits.** That's the default, and leaving it out makes the template smaller and auto-pickable.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:209:2. **Bundle a custom `states.yaml` when the template needs non-default states, artifact contracts, visit loops, program states, model fan-out, or team gates.** Follow `rhei-state-machine-writer`; do not stop at a prose summary of the machine.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:210:3. **If the rendered plan declares `**States:** <name>`, the bundled `states.yaml`'s `name` must match.** Auto-discovery keys off the YAML's `name` field.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:211:4. **Use `{{...}}` inside `states.yaml` only where the workflow needs parameterized control.** Common patterns: `visits: {{review_passes}}`, `model: {{model}}`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:213:6. **Do not validate or reason from raw templated `states.yaml` as if it were final YAML when it still contains placeholders.** Instantiate first, then inspect or validate the rendered `states.yaml` in the concrete workspace.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:217:1. **Instantiate before validating.** Template source files can contain MiniJinja placeholders; the authoritative thing to validate is the rendered workspace.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:218:2. **Run `rhei validate` on the instantiated workspace, not only `rhei instantiate --dry-run`.** Dry-run catches rendering errors; validation catches plan, state-machine, settings, artifact, and link errors in the concrete output.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:219:3. **Run `rhei run <instantiated-workspace> --dry-run` before returning a runnable template.** This checks the orchestrator-facing shape without spawning agents, callbacks, or programs.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:221:5. **Keep the values file used for the example or document it in the example README.** Reviewers should be able to reproduce the exact non-scalar input shape that was validated.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:225:1. **Only bundle `settings.json` when the template references MCP servers, skills, or agent profiles that aren't guaranteed to exist in the user's global config.** Otherwise leave it out.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:227:3. **Every MCP or skill id referenced by the bundled `states.yaml` must be declared here or in the user's global settings.** `rhei validate` (invoked post-instantiation) surfaces dangling references.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:228:4. **Write `settings.json` at the root of the template.** `rhei instantiate` moves it to `.rhei/settings.json` in the output automatically.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:232:1. **Bundle scripts and runbooks the state machine references from callbacks** (`on_leave`, `on_enter`, or `program` states).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:234:3. **Avoid bundling anything the user can reasonably supply themselves.** Smaller templates are easier to audit.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:238:1. Confirm the workflow, parameters, and state-machine scope with the user.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:240:3. Draft `template.yaml` with the minimum required inputs.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:242:5. Decide whether to bundle `states.yaml`. If yes, apply `rhei-state-machine-writer` to produce the complete machine body, wire in `{{...}}` interpolations where needed, and add the state machine diagram as a comment block at the top of the file.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:243:6. Decide whether to bundle `settings.json`. If yes, declare MCP servers, skills, and `defaults` that match the state machine.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:244:7. Place the template in a discoverable directory (see *File Placement*).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:245:8. Smoke-render with `rhei instantiate <template> --dry-run --set ...` and fix rendering errors. For array or object inputs, use `--values <file>` in at least one smoke render.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:246:9. Write `README.md` at the template root (inputs table, per-task paths through the state machine, flow, instantiate command, link to the example).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:247:10. Generate the pre-rendered example into `examples/<template-name>-example/` and overwrite its README with an example-specific one.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:248:11. Validate the instantiated example with `rhei validate examples/<template-name>-example/`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:249:12. Run `rhei run examples/<template-name>-example/ --dry-run` and fix any execution-shape errors before returning.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:250:13. Repeat instantiate + validate + run-dry-run for at least two other input combinations to catch branches the example doesn't cover.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:254:When returning a template in chat instead of editing files directly, print a file-by-file artifact list. Include every required file as a fenced block with its path. If a custom state machine is needed, one of those blocks must be `<template>/states.yaml` and must contain the full YAML, including the top comment diagram. If no custom state machine is needed, say explicitly that the template intentionally uses the built-in `rhei` machine and therefore omits `states.yaml`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:256:Do not describe a custom state machine only in prose, and do not leave `states.yaml` for a later step unless the user explicitly asks for an outline instead of a complete template.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:260:Before returning the template, verify:
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:263:- `template.yaml` declares `name`, `version`, `description`, and optionally `inputs`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:266:- `type: array` inputs declare `items`; `validate` is only present on scalar types.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:271:- Runtime `{name}` variables that pass through instantiation are valid against the active state machine's variable namespace (`{task_id}`, `{task_title}`, `{visit_count}`, `{visits}`, `{model}`, `{input.<name>.path}`, `{output.<name>.path}`, `{meta.<key>}`).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:272:- If `states.yaml` is bundled and the rendered plan declares `**States:** <name>`, the YAML's `name` field matches `<name>`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:273:- If the workflow needs a custom state machine, `states.yaml` exists as a concrete artifact in the template output; it is not merely described in README text or the final response.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:274:- If `states.yaml` contains `{{...}}` placeholders, inspection and CLI validation are performed against the rendered workspace's `states.yaml`, not the raw template source.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:275:- If `states.yaml` is bundled, it passes the state-machine-writer validation checklist (profiles, node_policy, terminal reachability, etc.).
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:276:- If `settings.json` is bundled, it is valid JSON after rendering and every MCP / skill / agent id referenced by `states.yaml` is declared.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:277:- `rhei instantiate <template> --dry-run ...` succeeds.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:279:- The rendered workspace passes `rhei validate <instantiated-workspace>`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:280:- The rendered workspace passes `rhei run <instantiated-workspace> --dry-run`.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:281:- `<template>/README.md` exists and covers: one-paragraph summary, inputs table, per-task paths through the state machine, numbered flow, canonical `rhei instantiate` command, and a link to the pre-rendered example.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:282:- If `states.yaml` is bundled, it begins with an ASCII state machine diagram as a YAML comment block covering states, transitions, initial / final / gating markers, fan-out points, and per-task paths.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:283:- A pre-rendered example under `examples/<template-name>-example/` exists, was generated by `rhei instantiate`, has an example-specific `README.md` (inputs used, validate command, regenerate command), and passes `rhei validate <example-path>` as shipped.
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:287:Templates are resolved by `rhei instantiate <name>` in this order (first match wins):
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:289:| Priority | Location | Scope |
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:291:| 1 | `<project>/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/` | Project-local |
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:292:| 2 | `~/.agents/rhei/templates/<name>/` | User-global |
skills/rhei-template-writer/SKILL.md:294:Place project-scoped templates under `.agents/rhei/templates/` so the rest of the team picks them up from the checkout. Place personal templates under `~/.agents/rhei/templates/` so they're available across projects. A template can also be instantiated directly from an arbitrary filesystem path (`rhei instantiate ./path/to/template/`) — useful for authoring and review.
