skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Create, refactor, and validate Rhei Plan markdown documents for project execution. Use when users ask for implementation plans, task breakdowns, roadmap-to-task conversion, dependency cleanup, or status updates in a strict, structured plan format with task states and prerequisites.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:22:- Optionally emit `**States:** <state-machine-name>` as the first non-empty line after the H1 to declare which state machine the plan follows. Omit to use the built-in `rhei` state machine.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:42:**Prior:** Task <id>, Task <id>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:50:- Place `**Prior:**` second when present.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:51:- Omit `**Prior:**` when no prerequisites exist.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:59:Run `rhei states` in the project to discover the allowed state values, their agent instructions, and the declared transitions for the state machine the plan will follow. Use `rhei states --state-machine <path>` to target a specific YAML file (for example, the one referenced by a plan's `**States:**` line), and `rhei states --json` when machine-readable output is preferred. Use only state values reported by that command, follow the printed instructions when describing task work, and respect the declared transitions when choosing initial states.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:61:If the `rhei` CLI is unavailable in the project, fall back to reading the state machine YAML file directly (typically `docs/states.yaml`, or the file referenced by `**States:**`). If the project does not define its own state machine, fall back to the default Rhei state set documented in [default-states.md](references/default-states.md).
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:63:Each node's initial state comes from the machine's `profiles.<name>.initial` via `node_policy` — **not** from a state-level `initial: true` flag. In the built-in `rhei` machine, the initial state is `draft`. When authoring a new plan under that machine, every task starts in `draft`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:75:For state machines that declare a `visits` budget on a state, a counted-visit suffix (`-<n>`, with `n >= 2`) may appear in the rendered state value for later visits. The plan writer normally does not author these — they accumulate at runtime.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:87:Decompose a task with nested `Task` nodes at a deeper heading level. Child nodes use the same block shape as roots but with a dotted id that extends the parent:
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:90:#### Task <parent>.<child>: <title>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:99:- The child id extends the parent id by exactly one new segment, separated by `.`: `1.1`, `1.2.3`, `api.cache`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:100:- Numeric children increment from `1` within their parent; named children use short identifiers. Mixed numeric/named segments are allowed as long as depth matches.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:101:- Sibling ids must be unique under the same parent.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:147:- If present, place `**States:** <state-machine-name>` as the first non-empty line after the H1, before any frontmatter or H2 section.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:151:- Format every child task node as `#### <Kind> <parent>.<child>: <title>` (and deeper levels at H5/H6 when `structure.maxLevels` permits).
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:153:- Place `**Prior:**` only after `**State:**` when present.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:155:- Reference only existing tasks in each `**Prior:**` line. In a Directory Workspace, references resolve across the merged workspace graph.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:156:- Keep dependencies acyclic. A task must not self-reference and must not list its parent or any ancestor as `**Prior:**`. When follow-up work must wait for a parent task to complete, author it as a top-level sibling instead of a child.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:158:- Each child id extends its parent id by exactly one segment; sibling ids under the same parent are unique.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:160:- Emit no metadata fields beyond `**State:**` and `**Prior:**`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:164:When the CLI is available, run `rhei validate <plan>` after writing — it performs the full grammar, state, dependency, link, and terminal-coherence checks the checklist only approximates.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:179:6. Run `rhei validate` after editing.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:196:The state machine defines what happens at each stage of a task's lifecycle — read it before deciding granularity. A machine with heavyweight review gates (multi-agent review, human sign-off, multi-team handoffs) justifies larger tasks to amortize that overhead. A lightweight machine (implement → done) allows smaller, more focused tasks. Match task size to the cost of moving through the states.
