### .agents/rhei/templates/changeset-review/states.yaml
# State machine diagram
# ─────────────────────
#
# Legend:  [initial]  [final]  [gating — agent stops, waits for human]
#          ═══►  happy-path transition
#          ╌╌►  opt-out transition (human closes with no fixes)
#
#   ┌──────────────┐                     ┌───────────────────┐
#   │ split        │ ═══ overview + ═══► │ completed [final] │
#   │ [initial]    │     parts spawn     └───────────────────┘
#   └──────────────┘
#
#   ┌──────────────┐                     ┌───────────────────┐
#   │ review       │ ═══════════════════►│ completed [final] │
#   │ (all_targets:│    per-target pass  └───────────────────┘
#   │ review_      │    fan-out
#   │  models)     │
#   └──────────────┘
#
#   ┌──────────────┐   ┌──────────────────┐  triaged  ┌───────────┐
#   │ aggregate    │══►│ human-review     │══════════►│ fix-spawn │═══►┐
#   │ (Prior = all │   │ [gating]         │╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌► └───────────┘    │
#   │  reviews)    │   └──────────────────┘ no fixes          │        │
#   └──────────────┘                                          ▼        ▼
#                                                        ┌───────────────────┐
#                                                        │ completed [final] │
#                                                        └───────────────────┘
#
#   Fix task path (pre/post stages are conditional on template inputs):
#
#   ┌────────────────────┐       ┌─────┐       ┌────────────┐       ┌───────────┐
#   │ prepare-workspace  │══════►│ fix │══════►│ commit-fix │══════►│ completed │
#   │ (if fix_prepare    │       │     │       │ (if fix_   │       │  [final]  │
#   │  ≠ none)           │       │     │       │  commit ≠  │       └───────────┘
#   └────────────────────┘       └─────┘       │  none)     │
#           ▲                       │          └────────────┘
#           │                       │                 ▲
#   entry when fix_prepare ≠ none   │ skip commit-fix ┘  (fix_commit == none:
#   else entry is `fix`             │                     fix ═══► completed)
#                                   ▼
#                              ┌───────────┐
#                              │ completed │
#                              │  [final]  │
#                              └───────────┘
#
#   any non-final state ═══► ┌───────────────────┐
#                            │ cancelled [final] │
#                            └───────────────────┘
#
# Per-task paths:
#   coordinator:   split → completed
#   review-<slug>: review → completed                   (all_targets fan-out)
#   aggregate:     aggregate → human-review → fix-spawn → completed
#                                          ╌► completed (no fixes selected)
#   fix-<id>:      [prepare-workspace →] fix [→ commit-fix] → completed
#                  (brackets denote optional stages toggled by fix_prepare
#                   and fix_commit inputs)

name: changeset-review
version: 1.0.0

states:
  split:
    description: Coordinator writes an architectural overview of the change, then spawns one review task per logical part plus an aggregator task.
    initial: true
    instructions: |
      You are the change-review coordinator for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      First, treat this instantiated workspace as a scratchpad. Resolve the
      repository root with `git rev-parse --show-toplevel` from the current
      workspace and use that repository root for all VCS commands and all
      repository file lookups (`docs/specs`, source files, ADRs, etc.). Do
      not assume the workspace directory itself contains the repository
      files.

      0. Resolve `{{change_ref}}` to a concrete set of files and a diff.
         The reference can be any of:
           - a PR URL or PR number (e.g., `#42`, `org/repo#42`, full URL)
           - a branch name (compare against the project's default branch)
           - a commit SHA or range `base..head`
           - a path to a `.diff` or `.patch` file on disk
         Use the project's VCS tooling (`gh`, `git diff`, `git log`, etc.)
         from the resolved repository root to produce the list of changed
         files and the unified diff. If the reference is ambiguous, resolve
         it the narrowest way consistent with the user's intent and note the
         assumption in the overview.
      1. Produce an architectural overview of the resolved change.
         Write it to `{output.architecture-overview.path}` covering:
           - the user-visible or operational intent of the change
           - the subsystems touched and how responsibility moves between
             them (component diagram in text is fine)
           - new or changed public interfaces, data models, and contracts
           - cross-cutting concerns introduced (caching, locking,
             migrations, feature flags, deployment ordering)
           - risks the reviewers should keep in mind while reading parts

         Include a "Metadata" subsection that captures, verbatim or
         summarized:
           - the resolved repository root path
           - whether the change is accompanied by a PR (capture title and
             body if so; leave a `PR: none` note otherwise)
           - the list of commit subjects + bodies on the change
           - whether the project has specs (look for `docs/specs/`,
             `specs/`, `SPEC.md`, ADR directories, or equivalents) that
             intersect the subsystems touched — record the intersecting
             spec file paths or `Specs: none`

         Include a "User-facing?" call: does the change alter behavior
         visible to users or operators (public API, CLI, UI, error
         messages, defaults, configuration surface, docs-worthy
         behavior)? Record `yes` or `no` with a one-line justification.

         This is the reviewer's mental map — keep it short and concrete.

      2. Using the overview, decide which parts need to be reviewed.
         The part set is a mix of **code parts** and **meta parts**.

         Code parts:
           - Split the diff into logical parts (by subsystem, by file
             cluster, or by concern). Aim for parts small enough to
             review thoroughly in one pass.

         Meta parts — add each only when the condition holds:
           - `pr-description` — add **if** the change arrived as a PR.
             The task reviews the PR title and body for clarity,
             completeness, release-note readiness, missing context, and
             any security disclosure or breaking-change notes that
             should be called out.
           - `commit-messages` — add **always**. The task reviews the
             list of commit messages for clarity, atomicity, traceability
             (issue / ticket references), and "mess" — `wip`, `fixup`,
             `address review comments`, typo-level fixups, or
             conflicting intent that should be squashed or rewritten
             before merge.
           - `documentation` — add **if** "User-facing?" is `yes`.
             Scope is README, CHANGELOG, `docs/`, API reference, CLI
             help, and any other user-facing docs that must keep up
             with the change. The task body lists the specific doc
             files the coordinator believes need updating or verifying.
           - `spec` — add **if** the project has specs that intersect
             the subsystems touched. Scope is those specific spec files.
             The task reviews whether the change is consistent with the
             spec, whether the spec needs an update, and whether
             assumptions baked into the change match documented behavior.

      3. Write a short manifest of parts to `{output.parts-manifest.path}`.
         Each entry records:
           - a stable slug (lowercase, hyphenated)
           - `type: code | pr-description | commit-messages | documentation | spec`
           - the files, paths, or materials in scope (for meta parts,
             inline the PR body or commit messages directly so the
             reviewer does not have to re-fetch them)
           - a one-line summary of what to focus on
           - a pointer back to the relevant section of the overview

      4. For every part, append a task file under `tasks/` named
         `NN-review-<slug>.md` with:
           - `### Task review-<slug>: Review <part title>`
           - `**State:** review`
           - `**Prior:** Task {task_id}`
           - a body that:
             * restates the part scope and cites the overview section
             * for code parts, lists the files in scope
             * for meta parts, inlines the materials to review (PR
               body, commit messages) or lists the specific doc / spec
               files in scope
             * calls out the specific questions the reviewer must answer
               (the bullet list under each meta part above)

      5. Append one aggregator task file under `tasks/`:
           - `### Task aggregate: Aggregate and score review findings`
           - `**State:** aggregate`
           - `**Prior:**` listing every `review-<slug>` task you just
             created (code + meta), so it only runs after every review
             completes.

      6. Transition to `completed`.
    outputs:
      - name: architecture-overview
        path: runtime/manifests/{task_id}-architecture.md

