name: hourly-human-intervention
version: 1.1.0

states:
  fetch:
    description: Fetch all human-intervention items of one GitHub kind and classify them into root-cause classes.
    initial: true
    target: "{{analysis_target}}"
    instructions: |
      Fetch and classify Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      Work from the coordination workspace root. Treat GitHub as the source of
      truth for `{{repo}}` items labeled `{{label}}`.

      Determine from the task body whether this task fetches issues or pull
      requests.

      For issues, fetch every open issue labeled `{{label}}`. Include:
      - number, title, URL, author, assignees, labels, created/updated times
      - body, recent comments, linked PRs when available
      - any Forge human-intervention comment, log URL, branch, or artifact

      For pull requests, fetch every open PR labeled `{{label}}`. Include:
      - number, title, URL, author, assignees, labels, created/updated times
      - body, recent comments, review comments, review decision, CI state
      - head branch, changed files, diff summary, and any Forge comment/log

      Use `gh` commands with pagination when necessary. Do not silently stop at
      the first page.

      Write the raw inventory to `{output.inventory.path}`.

      Classify items into root-cause classes that can share one investigation
      and one fix path. CI failures are the exception: create one child task
      per CI failure item because each needs an independent restart/rerun and
      recheck before it is fixed or completed. Class names should be stable
      lowercase slugs. Useful route hints are:
      - `ci-failure`: the item is blocked by GitHub Actions, status checks, a
        runner log, or a CI-created failure issue such as
        `fails-javac-compile`, `fails-java-run`, or
        `fails-native-image-run`.
      - `human-github`: the item lacks information, needs product/reviewer
        judgment, or cannot be fixed safely by automation.
      - `forge`: the fix likely belongs in `{{forge_checkout}}`, including
        metadata, tests, Forge workflows, prompts, scripts, or PR automation.
      - `graalvm`: the fix likely belongs in `{{graalvm_ce_checkout}}` or
        `{{graalvm_ee_checkout}}`, including Native Image, SVM, CE, EE, or the
        local GraalVM build.

      Write the classification manifest to `{output.classification.path}` with
      one section per class:
      - class slug
      - route hint
      - item numbers and URLs
      - existing RHEI handoff/publication comments, if any
      - shared symptoms
      - evidence gathered
      - why these items belong together

      For CI failures, include the failing check name, workflow run URL, job
      URL, rerun/restart command if one can be derived, and whether the first
      evidence looks like infra, transient flakiness, or a real test/build
      failure.

      Idempotency matters because this sweep runs hourly. If an item already has
      a recent RHEI handoff, publication, or "blocked waiting for human" comment
      and no newer user/CI/review activity changes the evidence, classify it as
      already handled and do not append another child task for it.

      For each non-empty non-CI class, append one child task under the current
      task in the same task file. Use this shape:

        #### Task {task_id}.<class-slug>: Analyze <class title>
        **State:** deep-analysis
        **Prior:** Task {task_id}

        - Source kind: issues or pull requests

### .agents/rhei/templates/multi-model-analysis/states.yaml
name: multi-model-analysis
version: 1.0.0

states:
  analyze:
    description: Run one independent analysis pass per configured agent target.
    all_targets:
{% for analysis_agent in agents %}
      - {{ analysis_agent.selector }}
{% endfor %}
    personality: |
      You are {agent} in mode {agent.mode} running target {target}.
      Do not imitate the other targets. Produce your own reasoning,
      assumptions, risks, and recommendation.
    instructions: |
      Analyze Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      Read the task body carefully and produce a self-contained analysis note at
      `{output.analysis.path}`. The note should include:
      - task interpretation
      - assumptions and unknowns
      - key observations
      - risks or tradeoffs
      - recommended next action

      If your toolset does not expose a dedicated file-write tool, create the
      output file using available shell or filesystem commands instead.
    outputs:
      - name: analysis
        path: {{analysis_output_dir}}/{target.slug}.md
        description: Analysis note for the current target-specific pass

  summarize:
    description: Claude synthesizes the independent target analyses into one final document.
    target: {{summary_agent}}
    personality: |
      You are Claude acting as the final synthesizer. Read the analysis notes,
      reconcile overlap and disagreement, and produce one clear final document
      for the user.
    instructions: |
      Summarize Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      Read:
{% for analysis_agent in agents %}
      - `{input.{{ analysis_agent.id }}-analysis.path}`
{% endfor %}

      Write a final document to `{output.final-document.path}` that:
      - synthesizes the shared conclusions
      - calls out meaningful disagreements or uncertainty
      - recommends the final answer or next step

      If your toolset does not expose a dedicated file-write tool, create the
      output file using available shell or filesystem commands instead.
    inputs:
{% for analysis_agent in agents %}
      - name: {{ analysis_agent.id }}-analysis
        path: {{analysis_output_dir}}/{{ analysis_agent.selector|slug }}.md
        description: {{ analysis_agent.label }}
{% endfor %}
    outputs:
      - name: final-document
        path: {{final_document_path}}
        description: Final synthesized document across all model analysis notes

  completed:
    description: The multi-model analysis workflow is finished.
    instructions: |
      No more action is required.
    final: true

  cancelled:
    description: The workflow was cancelled.
    instructions: |
      Stop work and leave existing artifacts unchanged.
    final: true

transitions:
  - from: analyze
    to: summarize
    description: All target-specific analysis notes were written.

  - from: analyze
    to: cancelled
    description: Cancel the workflow during the analysis fanout.

  - from: summarize
    to: completed
    description: Claude wrote the final synthesized document.

  - from: summarize
    to: cancelled
    description: Cancel the workflow during synthesis.

profiles:
  workspace:
    initial: completed
    allowed:
      - completed

  analysis-task:
    initial: analyze
    allowed:
      - analyze
      - summarize
      - completed
      - cancelled

node_policy:
  root: workspace
  default: analysis-task
  by_type:
    task: analysis-task

### .agents/rhei/templates/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/states.yaml
# State machine diagram
# ---------------------
#
# Legend:
#   [initial]  first state for every audit partition
#   [gating]   human-only state; agents must stop
#   [final]    terminal reconciliation outcome
#
#   scope-spec [initial]
#       |
#       v
#   compare-implementation
#       |        ^
#       v        |
#   elaborate-discrepancies
#       |        ^
#       v        |
#   propose-reconciliation
#       |
#       v
#   human-decision [gating]
#       |
#       +--> update-spec [final]
#       +--> update-implementation [final]
#       +--> update-both [final]
#       +--> defer-follow-up [final]
#       +--> no-change [final]
#       +--> cancelled [final]
#
# Recovery transitions:
#   compare-implementation -> scope-spec
#   elaborate-discrepancies -> compare-implementation
#   propose-reconciliation -> elaborate-discrepancies
#   scope-spec / compare-implementation / elaborate-discrepancies /
#     propose-reconciliation -> cancelled
#
# Fan-out points:
#   None. The template creates multiple independent partition tasks, and
#   `concurrent: true` allows parallel work across partitions.
#   Autonomous work states run on {{audit_target}}.
#
# Per-task path:
#   audit partition:
#     scope-spec -> compare-implementation -> elaborate-discrepancies ->
#     propose-reconciliation -> human-decision -> human-selected final state

name: spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit
version: 1.0
personality: |
  You are auditing {{subject}}'s written specification against the
  implementation. Be precise, cite concrete files and symbols, and distinguish
  real discrepancies from missing tests, ambiguous prose, or intentional design
  choices.

states:
  scope-spec:
    description: Identify the normative spec clauses and implementation surfaces for this partition.
    target: {{audit_target}}
    concurrent: true
    agent_timeout: 1h
    instructions: |
      Read the task description and enumerate the exact specification files,
      sections, and normative claims that belong to this partition. Map each
      claim to the implementation files, tests, fixtures, templates, skills,
      and user-facing commands that should satisfy it.

      Write the scope inventory to {output.scope.path}. Include enough section
      names, file paths, command names, and symbol names for the next state to
      compare behavior without rediscovering the partition boundaries.
    outputs:
      - name: scope
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/scope.md
        format: markdown

  compare-implementation:
    description: Compare the scoped specification claims against code, tests, and command behavior.
    target: {{audit_target}}
    concurrent: true
    agent_timeout: 2h
    inputs:
      - name: scope
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/scope.md
        format: markdown
    outputs:
      - name: discrepancies
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/discrepancies.md
        format: markdown
    instructions: |
      Use {input.scope.path} as the partition boundary. For each scoped claim,
      compare the spec against implementation code, tests, fixtures, templates,
      skills, and CLI behavior where practical.

      Write {output.discrepancies.path}. Classify each finding as one of:
      implementation-diverges, spec-stale, ambiguous-spec, missing-validation,
      missing-test, or no-discrepancy. Include evidence with concrete file
      paths and line numbers where possible. Do not propose fixes yet.

  elaborate-discrepancies:
    description: Turn raw discrepancies into actionable explanations with risk and impact.
    target: {{audit_target}}
    concurrent: true
    agent_timeout: 1h
    inputs:
      - name: discrepancies
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/discrepancies.md
        format: markdown
    outputs:
      - name: elaboration
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/elaboration.md
        format: markdown
    instructions: |
      Read {input.discrepancies.path}. For each non-empty discrepancy, explain:
      the exact mismatch, why it matters, who or what is affected, whether the
      risk is user-facing or internal, and what verification currently exists.

      Write {output.elaboration.path}. Merge duplicates, mark weak findings as
      tentative, and explicitly record areas where no discrepancy was found.
      Do not pick a reconciliation strategy yet.

  propose-reconciliation:
    description: Propose how to reconcile each discrepancy before human decision.
    target: {{audit_target}}
    concurrent: true
    agent_timeout: 1h
    inputs:
      - name: elaboration
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/elaboration.md
        format: markdown
    outputs:
      - name: proposal
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/proposal.md
        format: markdown
    instructions: |
      Read {input.elaboration.path}. For each discrepancy, propose one primary
      reconciliation and any credible alternative.

      Write {output.proposal.path}. Each proposal must name one of these
      human decision options: update-spec, update-implementation, update-both,
      defer-follow-up, or no-change. Include concrete next edits or follow-up
      tasks, expected tests, and the reason the proposed option is preferable.

  human-decision:
    description: Human chooses how to reconcile the proposed discrepancies.
    gating: true
    inputs:
      - name: proposal
        path: runtime/spec-implementation-discrepancy-audit/{task_id}/proposal.md
        format: markdown
    instructions: |
      Stop autonomous work. A human must read {input.proposal.path} and choose
      one reconciliation outcome by explicitly transitioning the task to one of:

      - update-spec: the implementation is accepted as source of truth and the
        spec should be edited to match.
      - update-implementation: the spec is accepted as source of truth and code,
        tests, or behavior should change.
      - update-both: both sides need clarification or adjustment.
      - defer-follow-up: record the issue for later without reconciling now.
      - no-change: reject the discrepancy as intentional, obsolete, or not a
        real mismatch.
      - cancelled: abandon this partition.

      Do not transition out of this state autonomously.

  update-spec:
    description: Human selected the spec-update reconciliation path.
    final: true

  update-implementation:
    description: Human selected the implementation-update reconciliation path.
    final: true

  update-both:
    description: Human selected a combined spec and implementation reconciliation path.
    final: true

  defer-follow-up:
    description: Human deferred reconciliation into follow-up tracking.
    final: true


### .agents/rhei/templates/spec-review/states.yaml
name: spec-review
version: 1.0.0

states:
  review:
    description: Review the specification and produce findings.
    agent: codex
    instructions: |
      Review pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      Read the specification at `{{spec}}` and review it for:
      - Internal consistency (do definitions, examples, and grammar agree?)
      - Completeness (are edge cases, error handling, and defaults specified?)
      - Correctness (are claims accurate given the rest of the project?)
      - Clarity (can an implementer build from this without guessing?)
      {{criteria}}
      Stay scoped to `{{spec}}` and files that it explicitly references.
      Do not broaden into unrelated repository-wide review.

      Write your findings to `{output.review-notes.path}`.
      Record only the most important findings for this pass.
      Each finding should state the section, the issue, and a concrete suggestion.
      After writing the artifact, immediately transition to `fix`.
    initial: true
    visits: 2
    outputs:
      - name: review-notes
        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
        description: Review findings for this pass

  fix:
    description: Fix the specification based on review findings.
    agent: codex
    instructions: |
      Fix pass {visit_count} of {visits} for Task {task_id}: {task_title}.

      Read the review findings at `{input.review-notes.path}`.
      Apply each suggested fix directly to the specification at `{{spec}}`.
      Keep changes limited to the target specification file unless a finding explicitly requires an adjacent referenced file.
      Write a summary of changes made to `{output.fix-summary.path}`.
      After writing the artifact, if there is another review pass remaining
      (you are in pass {visit_count} of {visits}), transition back to `review`;
      once every review-fix cycle is complete, transition to `completed`.
    visits: 2
    inputs:
      - name: review-notes
        path: runtime/reviews/task-{task_id}-review-{visit_count}.md
    outputs:
      - name: fix-summary
        path: runtime/fixes/task-{task_id}-fix-{visit_count}.md
        description: Summary of changes applied in this fix pass

  completed:
    description: Spec review and fixes complete.
    instructions: |
      Task {task_id} is complete. The specification has been reviewed and updated.
    final: true

  cancelled:
    description: Review cancelled.
    instructions: |
      Task {task_id} cancelled. No further action required.
    final: true

transitions:
  - from: review
    to: fix
    description: Review pass done, apply fixes to the spec.

  - from: fix
    to: review
    condition: visitCount < visits
    description: Return for another review pass.

  - from: fix
    to: completed
    condition: visitCount >= visits
    description: Both review-fix passes complete.

  - from: "*"
    to: cancelled
    description: Cancel from any state.

### .agents/rhei/templates/changeset-review/tasks/01-coordinate.md
### Task coordinate: Coordinate review of {{change_ref}}
**State:** split

Resolve `{{change_ref}}` (PR, branch, commit SHA, commit range, or diff
file) to a concrete set of changed files. Write an architectural overview
of the change, then split it into logical parts for focused review. For
all repository inspection, first resolve the Git toplevel from this
scratchpad workspace and use that repository root rather than the
workspace directory itself. For
each part, append a `review-<slug>` task to `tasks/` with `**State:** review`
and `**Prior:** Task coordinate`. Append one `aggregate` task with
`**State:** aggregate` and `**Prior:**` listing every `review-<slug>` task
you created. When the overview and parts manifest are written and all
follow-up tasks are appended, transition to `completed`.

### .agents/rhei/templates/hourly-human-intervention/tasks/01-fetch-issues.md
### Task fetch-issues: Fetch and classify human-intervention issues
**State:** fetch

Fetch every open GitHub issue in `{{repo}}` labeled `{{label}}`.

Use GitHub as the source of truth. Include the issue number, title, URL,
labels, assignees, author, body, recent comments, linked pull requests when
available, and any Forge human-intervention comment or log reference.

Classify issues into actionable root-cause classes. Prefer classes that share
one investigation and one fix path, such as:

- CI failure issues from GitHub Actions or status checks; create one child
  `ci-failure-triage` task per issue so each can be restarted and rechecked
- metadata or test change in `{{forge_checkout}}`
- Forge automation defect in `{{forge_checkout}}/forge`
- Native Image or GraalVM behavior in `{{graalvm_ce_checkout}}` or `{{graalvm_ee_checkout}}`
- missing external information or product decision requiring a human GitHub issue/comment

Append one child task under this task for each non-empty non-CI class, using
state `deep-analysis` and `**Prior:** Task fetch-issues`. Append one child
task per CI failure issue using state `ci-failure-triage` and `**Prior:** Task
fetch-issues`.

### .agents/rhei/templates/hourly-human-intervention/tasks/02-fetch-prs.md
### Task fetch-prs: Fetch and classify human-intervention pull requests
**State:** fetch

Fetch every open GitHub pull request in `{{repo}}` labeled `{{label}}`.

Use GitHub as the source of truth. Include the PR number, title, URL, labels,
assignees, author, body, review state, CI state, head branch, changed files,
recent comments, review comments, and any Forge human-intervention comment or
log reference.

Classify pull requests into actionable root-cause classes. Prefer classes that
share one investigation and one fix path, such as:

- CI failure PRs from GitHub Actions or status checks; create one child
  `ci-failure-triage` task per PR so each can be restarted and rechecked
- PR needs metadata, test, or Forge workflow changes in `{{forge_checkout}}`
- PR exposes a Forge automation defect in `{{forge_checkout}}/forge`
- PR exposes Native Image or GraalVM behavior in `{{graalvm_ce_checkout}}` or `{{graalvm_ee_checkout}}`
- PR needs human product/reviewer input on GitHub before automation continues

Append one child task under this task for each non-empty non-CI class, using
state `deep-analysis` and `**Prior:** Task fetch-prs`. Append one child task
per CI failure PR using state `ci-failure-triage` and `**Prior:** Task
fetch-prs`.

